        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>[16 Montague Street, London]</placeName>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>The experiments on the sense of smell in cats and dogs seem to me very good.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> From your previous note, I know you do not believe in the stories of cats returning home over unknown ground; but if such a case is mentioned in <hi rend="underline">Nature</hi>, I would suggest your sending your experiment to that journal for publication, as bearing on Mr. Wallace’s theory, which I am half inclined to admit.<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The date is established by a reference in the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10290.xml" resp="#mjhawkins" cert="high">letter from Arthur Nicols of 8 December 1875</ref> (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1163.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Calendar</hi></ref> no. 10290).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-8817F.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Arthur Nicols, [before 20 March 1873]</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">For Nicols’s doubts about <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4935.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Alfred Russel Wallace’s</ref> theory that cats could navigate by sense of smell, see his <ref target="./DCP-LETT-8780.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter of 21 February 1873</ref>. Nicols does not appear to have published his experiment before it appeared in his <hi rend="italic">Natural history sketches</hi> (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5874.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Nicols 1885</ref>, pp. 51–2).</note>
        </div>        
            
